									<article class="post_microfeature">
						
							<div class="post_header">
								<h3>New York's Roadside Attractions</h3>
								<a href="/post/prison-ship-martyrs-monument"><h2>Prison Ship Martyrs Monument</h2></a>
								<span class="author">by Erik Bryan</span>																	<a href="/post/prison-ship-martyrs-monument"><img src="http://www.themorningnews.org/images/content/articles/prison-ship-martyrs-monument-header.jpg" alt="Prison Ship Martyrs Monument"/></a>
									
																	<p>I took Tuesday afternoon off work to visit a historical site a short walk from my apartment in Brooklyn. It’d been raining that morning, so I had to avoid a lot of standing water and muddy patches as I walked through Fort Greene Park. The sky was still overcast and gloomy as I arrived at the Prison Ship Martyrs Monument at the highest point in the park. The gloominess was all too appropriate considering I was there to visit a memorial inside of which is a crypt holding the remains of thousands of Revolutionary War prisoners.</p>
															</div>
							
						<div class="post_content">
							
								
							
								
							
								
							
							
															<p>
	I&rsquo;d first heard about the site on <a href="http://www.themorningnews.org/post/st.-pauls-church">my outing to St. Paul&rsquo;s Church</a> in the Bronx. Frank, the lecturer at St. Paul&rsquo;s that day, told me about the memorial, and gave me contact information for one Martin Maher, Brooklyn&rsquo;s Chief of Staff for New York&rsquo;s Parks Department. Frank intimated that someone from the media, such as myself, might even be allowed to enter the crypt if I communicated via the proper channels. I admit to certain morbid fascinations, and I&rsquo;ve wanted to visit the memorial ever since.&nbsp;
								<span class="continue"><a href="/post/prison-ship-martyrs-monument">Continue Reading</a></span></p>
													</div>
					</article>
							
			
